ill take effect\nJune 15. when he will leave Washing\nton to take a rest before returning\nto the practice of law at New York.\nHis successor has not been selected.\nAGAINST LOWDEN.\nMissouri Negroes Claim He Refused\nTo Protect Race.\nBr tk> amoraoma nma.\nSt. Urals. June 4.\u2014The Missouri Re\npublican League club, an organisation\nof negroes, today made public a mem\norial Being sent to the Missouri dele\ngates to the republican national con\nvention aaking for the defeat of Low\nden. The negroes assert that Lowden\ntailed to protect them daring the\nSt Louia nee riots three years ago.\nEIGHT PAGES.\nA DEPUTY *HKRIFF QONtMW\nTHAT MAN CHARGBD WITH\nMUROCR BOUCATCg\nnr *S sasseMs* Pitta\nGreefry. Ctrto. J*a* fJfegMff s\non trial charged with ths murder of\nthe Shank family, can read aad Write,\nJ. K. Hamilton, a deputy sheriff aC\nWeld county, today testiCM. The dO-\n1 tense contended that he eauM aet\nread or write. The offtoer afiM ha arae\non duty in the convict camp la Bop\ntember when he met Miller. He \u00abNC*\nMiller, asking where Miller was ea*-\nployed. He testified that MBler\nwrote, \"at Adam shank**.\u201d\nPLANNING TO BUILD\nON GRAND AVffNUE\nCharts Olson, who owns the ha\u00dfdlag\nnow occupied by the offices of the\nPacific Market company, St'fiM Grand\navenue, and Frank and Lewie Holliday,\nwho own the fractional vacant lot at\n204, are planning on joining forces\ntor the erection of two-story baiMinga\non the two alteu. Mr. Olson teond\nthat it would cost about *4W mpre\nto remodel the pi-esent structure thah\nto tear it down and build fro** tito\nground up. and has decided upon 0e\nlatter course. The new building Wil!\nbe two stories high, with offices es\nboth floors, and will conform In out\nward appearance with the\nbuilding. a< the corner of SeconJ aad\nGrand avenue.\nWHL SETHf\nMOW\nWAGE DISPUTES BETWEEN MIN\nERS AND OPERATORS TO 0O\nTO WILSON COfiMIBBION\nevmoamnmmr\nWasMactoa. Mme i 4.-\u2018TW\u00bb jnueMint\nhas appointed a CommfMted e